  "prompt": "Is the system of money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, the system of money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. **Money laundering** is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This crime is prohibited because it enables criminals to profit from illegal activities (such as drug trafficking, fraud, terrorism, or corruption) while disguising the origin of the funds.\n\n### Key Laws and Frameworks Against Money Laundering:\n1. **International Standards**: The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CFT). Countries that are members of FATF or follow its guidelines implement laws to combat money laundering.\n\n2. **National Laws**: Most countries have specific legislation criminalizing money laundering. Examples include:\n   - The **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **USA PATRIOT Act** in the United States.\n   - The **Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA)** in the United Kingdom.\n   - The **Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA)** in India.\n\n3. **Penalties**: Money laundering is a serious criminal offense, punishable by significant fines, imprisonment, asset forfeiture, and other legal sanctions. Financial institutions and businesses involved in money laundering can also face severe penalties, including loss of licenses and reputational damage.\n\n4. **Preventive Measures**: Governments require financial institutions, businesses, and professionals (like lawyers and accountants) to implement AML measures, such as customer due diligence (CDD), record-keeping, and reporting suspicious transactions.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a crime designed to legitimize illicit funds, and it is strictly prohibited under national and international laws. Efforts to combat it are a critical part of global efforts to prevent financial crime and maintain the integrity of financial systems.",
